{
  "answer": "**Dunoyer summarizes his project in the introduction (ch. 0, §7) as \"to show liberty in its causes.\"**[^1]\n\nThis phrasing explicitly identifies the \"object of this work,\" distinguishing it from dogmatic approaches (e.g., rights-based claims or ideal governments) by presenting liberty instead as \"a result\" born from \"all our progress,\" particularly morality and industry.[^1] He reiterates this earlier, stating that his \"design is to show how they [industry and morality] give birth to human liberty,\"[^2] and frames the core thesis as \"we become *free* only by becoming *industrious* and *moral*.\"[^2]\n\n[^1]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [ch. 0, §7, par. p-2d4253](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/00-introduction/translation/#p-2d4253).\n[^2]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [ch. 0, §1, par. p-67acca](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/00-introduction/translation/#p-67acca).",
